x4freetext: Los Alamos Neutron Science Center/
Weapons Neutron Research (LANSCE/WNR)spallation neutron
source.
The WNR neutron source at a 30-degr. production
angle, provided the continuous-in-energy source of
neutrons. The 800-MeV proton beam was incident on a
water-cooled tungsten target 3 cm in diameter and 7 cm
long. Typical currents of 1.6 microamperes were used
with a micropulse spacing of 1.8 microseconds, a
macropulse width of 625 microseconds and a rate of 40
macropulses per second. The micropulse width is
approximately 200 ps
Thin, metallic, elemental foils with diameter of 10 cm
Charged-particle detected
by telescopes each consisting of a gas proportional
counter, a 500-micron silicon surface-barrier
detector, and a 3-cm thick CsI(Tl) scintillator read
out by a photodiode, placed at angles of 20, 60,
90 and 135 degrees
Time of flight was used to determine incident
neutron energy, E-dE method for charged particle
identification
Fission chamber located
16.32 meters from the source
From 2007NICE,2,1081: "...For these experiments, the
resolution of the gas counters was not sufficient to
separate isotopes of hydrogen ions or to separate 3He
from alpha particles...." (p.1082, bottom, left col.).
